1. Introduction¶

This is an authentic project submitted for the first homework of IE582. We are provided with time series data for 60 distinct stock prices. The price index for a corresponding stock is collected in roughly 15 minute intervals, although there are some missing data which requires us to perform missing data imputation. Further, the data is collected between 2012 and 2019. Since these are stock prices, the stocks price information is not updated on weekends. Therefore, roughly we have 60/15105=200 data points on each week. The missing data may be related to a system issue on the databasis, or an issue caused while the data is being downloaded. The following sections will describe the approach to the problem, and how descriptive analytics is performed as flexibly as possible.

I would like to write a function that performs missing data imputation as we desire. Therefore, we can proceed by choosing more than one stock price and perform missing data imputation as we desire. Lastly, I have added a parameter, winp, that corresponds to window paramater which allows us to decide according to how many forward and backward indices of a corresponding missing data that we are willing to take. After finding available data points, it will average them out. There are some more things to be parametrized, but I have not done so for decreasing the complexity and I deemed this way to be acceptable.

In [73]:
filler <- function(vec=bomba,winp){
  
  m <- which(is.na(vec))
  for(i in 1:length(m)){
    stopper <- FALSE
    k <- m[i]
    ind <- c((k-winp):(k-1),(k+1):(k+winp))
    while(stopper==FALSE){
      l <- vec[ind]
      if(sum(is.na(l))<=2){
        vec[k]=mean(l[which(!is.na(l))])
        stopper <- TRUE
      }
      else{
        badpts <- (is.na(l))
        indices <- which(badpts==1)
        if(sum(ind[(winp+1):(winp*2)]-k>6)>2){
          ind[(winp+1):(winp*2)] = ind[1:winp]
        }
        else if(sum(badpts)>0){
          for(j in 1:sum(badpts)){
            if(indices[j]<=winp){
              ind[indices[j]] <- ind[indices[j]] - 1 
            }
            else{
              ind[indices[j]] <- ind[indices[j]] + 1
            }
          }
        }
        else{
          stopper==TRUE
        }
        
      }
    }
    
  }
  return(vec)
}

It can be observed that the data is not following the weak stationarity properties, that is the mean does not seem to be constant over time. There is a trend associated with time. Further, the variance does not seem to be constant over time, it is fluctuating with respect to time. At last, the covariance or correlation indices with respect to lags seems to be changing with respect to time. Thus, the data is not even weakly stationary. One might be doing log transformation at first to exclude the "possible" multiplier of the error term associated with time or another phenomenon. I have tried log transformations and it does make the series stationary with respect to its variance. However, there is also the trend information to consider if we would like to fixate the mean as well. A moving average approach may be applied to remove the trend but I will stop here.

Upon performing PCA with 5 stock prices as raw stock prices and log returns of the stocks we can observe that the log returns seem to be independent of each other. The dimensionality reduction approach does not seem to work on log returns most likely because log-returns breaks the trend information and focuses on the log percentage changes. However, the PCA approach with raw prices seem to be capturing approximately 94% of the variance with two components. With PCA, the "principal components" are found with respect to the correlation information. Basically, we are trying to transform the four axes that correspond to each stock prices and explain the data in terms of new latent variables capturing underlying pattern in the data. One can observe that the first component includes -0.5 of stocks 2 to 5 which are all stocks except AEFES. The last component is a mixture of AEFES and ASELS. Since AEFES is not included in the first component, the model seems to be capturing the remaining large portion of the variance by including the excluded stock price from the first component. We can successfully reduce the dimension, i.e. if we were to include these 5 stock prices, to a dimension of 2 while securing around 94% of the variance which is extraordinary.

At last, I would like to present an efficient function I have solely written only using certain syntax information from the internet. For calculating Moving Window Correlation, I have decided to code a function that calculates the evolution of correlation information between a chosen stock and a set of stocks that do not include that chosen stock. Even if we were to include, it would not matter because correlation of a variable with itself is exactly 1 because how more correlated one can be than with herself :). Anyway, cutting the chit chat, I have four functions and two of them are passed on as arguments onto the others. This is to make the coding more elegant, and avoid issues that may upcome. The main purpose of this efficient function is to upon delivery of a matrix that includes information of stock price evolvings, and the chosen as well as the opposing stock prices it calculates and plots the stock price evolution with respect to each distinct month and year. Upon writing the function, I was delighted that I have written it flexibly because it becomes somewhat difficult to observe the information related to more than one stock prices on a graph. yearmaker <- function(yrs,datas){#Function for data preperation
  k <- c(as.Date("2012-10-10"))
  for(i in 1:length(yrs)){
    for(j in 1:12){
      m <- (year(datas)==yrs[i] & (month(datas)==j))
      if(sum(m) != 0){
        k <- c(k,as.Date(datas[which.min(m!=1)]))
      }
      else
        next
    }
  }
  k[-1]
}

windowcorrcalculator <- function(inp_m,z){
  k1 <- 1
  corvec <- rep(0,length(z))
  for(i in (z[1]):(z[length(z)]-1)){
    k2 <- which.min(inp_m[3,]<=i)
    corvec[i-z[1]+1] = cor(inp_m[1,k1:(k2-1)],inp_m[2,k1:(k2-1)])
    k1 <- k2
  }
  k2 <- length(inp_m[1,])
  corvec[i-z[1]+2] = cor(inp_m[1,k1:(k2)],inp_m[2,k1:(k2)])
  corvec
}

plotfnc <- function(matrixdata,dates,z="main",xaxis="dates",yaxis="Correlation Values",stockind=1, stockusage){
  if(length(stockusage) > 2 ){
    indicex <- stockusage
    indicex <- indicex[-which(stockusage==stockind)]
    plot(x=dates,y=matrixdata[1,],main=z,xlab=xaxis,ylab=yaxis,col=indicex[1],type="l",lty=2)
    points(x=dates,y=matrixdata[1,],col=indicex[1],pch=1,cex=0.4)
    for(i in 2:length(matrixdata[,1])){
      lines(x = dates, y=matrixdata[i,],type="l" ,lty=2, col=indicex[i])
      points(x=dates,y=matrixdata[i,],col=indicex[i],pch=indicex[i],cex=0.4)
      legend(x="top",
             legend = indicex,
             lty = 1,
             cex=0.50,
             col=indicex,
             pch=indicex,
             lwd=2,
             horiz=TRUE)
    }
  }
  else{
    indicex <- stockusage
    indicex <- indicex[-which(stockusage==stockind)]
    plot(x=dates,y=matrixdata[1,],main=paste(c("Monthly Corr btw ",stockusage[1],"and",stockusage[2])),xlab=xaxis,ylab=yaxis,col=indicex[1],type="l",lty=2)
    points(x=dates,y=matrixdata[1,],col=indicex[1],pch=1,cex=0.4)
  }
}

twostockswindow <- function(stockinfo=1,allstocks=c(1:20),yrs=c(2012,2013,2014),datamatrix,dates,f=windowcorrcalculator,g=plotfnc){
  stocks <- 1:length(allstocks)
  stocks = stocks[-stockinfo]
  summer <- length(dates)
  k <- length(datamatrix[,1])
  outpmat <- matrix(0,nrow=length(stocks),ncol=summer)
  for(i in 1:(length(allstocks)-1)){
    counter <- 1
    for(j in 1:(length(yrs)-1)){
      k1 <- which.min(datamatrix[k-2,] !=  yrs[j])
      k2 <- which.min(datamatrix[k-2,] <= yrs[j])
      z <- unique(datamatrix[(k-1),k1:(k2-1)])
      outpmat[i,(counter:(length(z)+counter-1))] <- f(datamatrix[c(stockinfo,stocks[i],k-1),k1:(k2-1)],z) 
      counter = counter + length(z)
      k1 <- k2
    }
    k2 <- which.max(cumsum(datamatrix[k-2,] == yrs[j+1]))
    z <- unique(datamatrix[(k-1),k1:(k2-1)])
    holder <- f(datamatrix[c(stockinfo,stocks[i],k-1),k1:k2],z)
    outpmat[i,(summer-length(holder) + 1):summer] <- holder
  }
  g(outpmat,dates,z=paste(c("Monthly Correlations for ",stockinfo, "and chosen stocks")),stockind=stockinfo,stockusage=allstocks)
}

Conclusions¶

We may conclude that the data is not stationary in its raw form, after necessary transformations it may be stationarized to some extent but we are not after time series analysis of a stock price. The correlation information between the stock prices seem to be changing drastically from month to month. However, using the raw form and PCA we were able to capture approximately 94% of the variance using only two components. Therefore if we were to use these five components, we could be able to reduce the variance even though the correlation information is changing unsteadily from month to month.
